<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Chorizanthe rigida</i> is a desert annual that grows up to 15 cm tall and blooms from February through June.  Cauline leaf blades become hard and thornlike as they age and are painful to step on, explaining the common name Devilâ€™s Spineflower.  Basal leaves of the spiny plant are long-petioled and often hairy (Hickman 1993).  Following winter to spring rain, the plant is bright green and grows quickly, and in summer the plant dries and becomes less noticeable.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Geraea canescens </i> is an annual plant that grows from 30 to 90 cm tall and blooms from February to May, or October to November. It has bright, golden yellow sunflower-like flowers on slender, hairy stems. It is a drought evasion plant that blooms in the rainy seasons and dies off after producing seeds (DesertUSA 2017). <br/>
<br/>
This alliance occurs throughout most of the warm deserts of North America. Stands occur on alluvial fans around playas in valley bottoms or near washes and less commonly on dissected, eroding alluvial fans. On well-developed pavement, the ground surface is covered with closely packed, interlocking rock fragments of gravels and cobbles. Desert pavement, though, exhibits spatial heterogeneity with six visually distinct surface mosaics identified, which have textural differences in surface rock size and percent soil cover -- varying from > 65% to < 20% cover of rock clasts on the ground surface (Wood et al. 2002). Desert varnish is characteristically seen on rock clasts of desert pavement and is a paper-thin coating of clay minerals, iron and manganese oxides, and other compounds that varies in color from orange to brown and black (Dorn 1991, 2007). <br/>
<br/>
A variable suite of native annual plants occur in this alliance, which are warm-season annuals that develop in the late winter and flower in the spring (and sometimes in the fall).  The number and timing of germinating plants are related to the amount of fall/winter precipitation and temperature.  Colorful spring displays of flowering plants occur in El Nino years, while plants are sparse in dry years.  Thus, annual plant cover may vary (e.g., from <1% to >20%) depending on the year, while desert scrub species occur at very low cover if present. However, small islands of woody perennials may exist, especially where pavements are intertwined with more densely vegetated, wash rivulets. This alliance varies in species composition across different areas of southeastern California and beyond, and more data collection and analysis are needed to describe associations. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
