    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-d). Stands are common in the valleys and bajadas of these subsections, including in the Imperial Valley and southwest of the Chocolate Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-p). Stands are scattered throughout the valleys and bajadas of these subsections including the Black Mountains, Death Valley, Owlshead Mountains, Silurian Valley, Devil's Playground, Superior Valley, Mojave Valley, Lucerne Valley, Twentynine Palms, and Pinto Basin.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Di). The alliance occurs uncommonly in the section; additional research is needed to determine associations.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Stands are common in the valleys and bajadas of these subsections including Rice Valley, Palo Verde Mesa, Chuckwalla Valley and Mountains, Palen Valley, Vidal Valley, and the Chocolate Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fa-c, Fe). Stands occur in Eureka Valley, Owens Valley, and other smaller valleys.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bp). The alliance occurs uncommonly in the section; additional research is needed to determine associations.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> These sparse desert environments are not typically disturbed by fire, except where non-native grasses and forbs have invaded and can carry fire. OHV and transportation corridors are the primary impacts to this alliance, while livestock grazing may be another impact. Annual plants of this alliance have flowers that attract bees and birds, and the seeds are an important food source for birds and rodents (DesertUSA 2017). </div>
</div>

    

    

